{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01837uS5w7RTRd5CLN2FK94T","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"Prompt file loading, variable substitution, and WorkflowTemplate abstraction.\n2\t\n3\tWhen the runner executes an :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.AgentTask`,\n4\tit needs to build the prompt the Claude Code subprocess will receive.\n5\tThat involves three steps:\n6\t\n7\t1. **Load** each file listed in ``AgentTask.prompts``, resolved\n8\t   relative to the workflow's directory.\n9\t2. **Concatenate** them with blank-line separators, preserving order.\n10\t3. **Substitute** ``{{PLACEHOLDER}}``-style tokens with values from\n11\t   the current :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.ExecutionContext`.\n12\t\n13\tThe placeholder syntax (``{{UPPERCASE_NAME}}``) is deliberately distinct\n14\tfrom Python's ``str.format`` ``{lowercase}`` style used by\n15\t``ExecutionContext.format_string`` — the two templating systems serve\n16\tdifferent purposes:\n17\t\n18\t- :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` is **strict**: unknown\n19\t  placeholders raise ``KeyError``. Used for commit messages and shell\n20\t  commands where typos must be caught early.\n21\t- :func:`substitute_placeholders` is **permissive**: unknown\n22\t  placeholders are left as-is. This lets agent prompts evolve\n23\t  incrementally — you can reference ``{{NEW_FIELD}}`` in a prompt\n24\t  before the context learns how to populate it, and the prompt still\n25\t  renders without exploding.\n26\t\n27\tThe split also prevents accidental collisions between Python format\n28\tstrings in Bash commands and agent-prompt placeholders.\n29\t\n30\t:class:`WorkflowTemplate` is the foundational primitive for PRD-227\n31\tworkflow templates. A template defines required opening tasks, a\n32\tconstrained middle slot, and required closing tasks. ``.compose()``\n33\tconcatenates ``[*open, *middle, *close]`` into a :class:`Workflow`,\n34\tvalidating the middle against ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``\n35\tconstraints.\n36\t\"\"\"\n37\t\n38\tfrom __future__ import annotations\n39\t\n40\timport re\n41\tfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n42\tfrom pathlib import Path\n43\tfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Mapping\n44\t\n45\tfrom .workflow import BuiltIn, Workflow\n46\t\n47\tif TYPE_CHECKING:\n48\t    from .workflow import ExecutionContext\n49\t\n50\t\n51\tPLACEHOLDER_RE = re.compile(r\"\\{\\{(\\w+)\\}\\}\")\n52\t\"\"\"Matches ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in prompt templates.\n53\t\n54\tThe captured group is the placeholder name (alphanumeric + underscore).\n55\tNon-matching sequences pass through unchanged, so literal ``{{ }}`` in\n56\tdocumentation or code blocks inside prompts survive the substitution.\n57\t\"\"\"\n58\t\n59\t\n60\tdef load_prompt_files(workflow_dir: Path, paths: list[str]) -> str:\n61\t    \"\"\"Read and concatenate prompt files from a workflow directory.\n62\t\n63\t    Each path in ``paths`` is resolved relative to ``workflow_dir`` and\n64\t    read as UTF-8. Results are joined with ``\"\\\\n\\\\n\"`` separators so the\n65\t    agent sees them as distinct sections rather than one run-on prompt.\n66\t\n67\t    Raises ``FileNotFoundError`` with the workflow directory in the\n68\t    message if any path doesn't resolve — typos in ``AgentTask.prompts``\n69\t    should fail loudly at runtime, not silently produce empty prompts.\n70\t    \"\"\"\n71\t    parts: list[str] = []\n72\t    for path in paths:\n73\t        full = workflow_dir / path\n74\t        if not full.exists():\n75\t            raise FileNotFoundError(\n76\t                f\"prompt file not found in workflow {workflow_dir.name!r}: {path} \"\n77\t                f\"(looked in {full})\"\n78\t            )\n79\t        parts.append(full.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\"))\n80\t    return \"\\n\\n\".join(parts)\n81\t\n82\t\n83\tdef substitute_placeholders(template: str, context: Mapping[str, object]) -> str:\n84\t    \"\"\"Replace ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in ``template`` using ``context``.\n85\t\n86\t    Unknown placeholders (names not in ``context``) are left unchanged.\n87\t    This is intentional — it lets prompt authors reference future\n88\t    placeholders without breaking the current rendering, and it means a\n89\t    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` reference in verify.md stays literal during\n90\t    the initial rendering pass (when no check has failed yet) and gets\n91\t    substituted only on retry.\n92\t\n93\t    Values are coerced to ``str`` via ``str()``, so integers, paths,\n94\t    and dataclass reprs all work without caller ceremony.\n95\t    \"\"\"\n96\t\n97\t    def replace(match: re.Match[str]) -> str:\n98\t        key = match.group(1)\n99\t        if key in context:\n100\t            return str(context[key])\n101\t        return match.group(0)  # leave unchanged\n102\t\n103\t    return PLACEHOLDER_RE.sub(replace, template)\n104\t\n105\t\n106\tdef compose_prompt(\n107\t    workflow: Workflow,\n108\t    prompts: list[str],\n109\t    execution_context: ExecutionContext,\n110\t    extras: Mapping[str, object] | None = None,\n111\t) -> str:\n112\t    \"\"\"End-to-end: load prompt files and substitute context placeholders.\n113\t\n114\t    The standard placeholder set populated from the ExecutionContext:\n115\t\n116\t    - ``{{PRD_ID}}`` — the PRD's id\n117\t    - ``{{PRD_TITLE}}`` — the PRD's title\n118\t    - ``{{PRD_PATH}}`` — absolute path to the PRD file\n119\t    - ``{{PRD_SLUG}}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n120\t    - ``{{BRANCH_NAME}}`` — the current branch name\n121\t    - ``{{BASE_REF}}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n122\t    - ``{{WORKTREE_PATH}}`` — the worktree path (or empty string if unset)\n123\t\n124\t    ``extras`` is merged into the context after the standard keys, so\n125\t    callers can inject ad-hoc values (e.g. ``CHECK_OUTPUT`` for retry\n126\t    prompts) without modifying the ExecutionContext.\n127\t\n128\t    Raises ``ValueError`` if the workflow has no ``workflow_dir`` set\n129\t    (shouldn't happen in practice — the loader sets it — but makes the\n130\t    failure explicit if someone constructs a Workflow by hand).\n131\t    \"\"\"\n132\t    if workflow.workflow_dir is None:\n133\t        raise ValueError(\n134\t            f\"workflow {workflow.name!r} has no workflow_dir; \"\n135\t            \"the loader normally sets this at import time\"\n136\t        )\n137\t\n138\t    raw = load_prompt_files(workflow.workflow_dir, prompts)\n139\t\n140\t    prd = execution_context.prd\n141\t    context: dict[str, object] = {\n142\t        \"PRD_ID\": prd.id,\n143\t        \"PRD_TITLE\": prd.title,\n144\t        \"PRD_PATH\": str(prd.path),\n145\t        \"PRD_SLUG\": prd.slug,\n146\t        \"BRANCH_NAME\": execution_context.branch_name,\n147\t        \"BASE_REF\": execution_context.base_ref,\n148\t        \"WORKTREE_PATH\": (\n149\t            str(execution_context.worktree_path)\n150\t            if execution_context.worktree_path\n151\t            else \"\"\n152\t        ),\n153\t    }\n154\t    if extras:\n155\t        context.update(extras)\n156\t\n157\t    return substitute_placeholders(raw, context)\n158\t\n159\t\n160\t# ---------- WorkflowTemplate ----------\n161\t\n162\t\n163\tclass TemplateViolation(Exception):\n164\t    \"\"\"Raised when a composed middle violates the template's constraints.\"\"\"\n165\t\n166\t\n167\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n168\tclass WorkflowTemplate:\n169\t    \"\"\"A reusable recipe that stamps out :class:`Workflow` instances.\n170\t\n171\t    A template defines:\n172\t\n173\t    - Required **opening** tasks that always run first (``open``).\n174\t    - A constrained **middle** slot for caller-supplied tasks.\n175\t    - Required **closing** tasks that always run last (``close``).\n176\t\n177\t    :meth:`compose` validates the caller's middle tasks against\n178\t    ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``, then returns a\n179\t    :class:`Workflow` whose task list is ``[*open, *middle, *close]``\n180\t    with ``template_name`` set to this template's ``name``.\n181\t    \"\"\"\n182\t\n183\t    name: str\n184\t    description: str\n185\t    open: list[BuiltIn]\n186\t    close: list[BuiltIn]\n187\t    middle_kinds: list[type] = field(default_factory=list)\n188\t    middle_required: dict[type, tuple[int, int | None]] = field(default_factory=dict)\n189\t\n190\t    def compose(\n191\t        self,\n192\t        name: str,\n193\t        description: str,\n194\t        applies_to: Callable[..., bool],\n195\t        priority: int,\n196\t        middle: list[Any],\n197\t    ) -> Workflow:\n198\t        \"\"\"Validate ``middle`` and return a complete :class:`Workflow`.\n199\t\n200\t        Parameters match :class:`Workflow` constructor arguments for the\n201\t        caller-supplied fields. ``tasks`` and ``template_name`` are set\n202\t        by this method.\n203\t\n204\t        Raises :class:`TemplateViolation` if any task in ``middle`` is\n205\t        not an instance of one of ``middle_kinds``, or if the count of\n206\t        any required kind falls outside the ``middle_required`` bounds.\n207\t        \"\"\"\n208\t        self._validate_middle(middle)\n209\t        return Workflow(\n210\t            name=name,\n211\t            description=description,\n212\t            applies_to=applies_to,\n213\t            priority=priority,\n214\t            tasks=[*self.open, *middle, *self.close],\n215\t            template_name=self.name,\n216\t        )\n217\t\n218\t    def _validate_middle(self, middle: list[Any]) -> None:\n219\t        if self.middle_kinds:\n220\t            for task in middle:\n221\t                if not isinstance(task, tuple(self.middle_kinds)):\n222\t                    raise TemplateViolation(\n223\t                        f\"Task {task!r} is not an allowed middle kind \"\n224\t                        f\"(allowed: {[k.__name__ for k in self.middle_kinds]})\"\n225\t                    )\n226\t        for kind, (min_count, max_count) in self.middle_required.items():\n227\t            actual = sum(1 for t in middle if isinstance(t, kind))\n228\t            if actual < min_count:\n229\t                raise TemplateViolation(\n230\t                    f\"Template requires at least {min_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n231\t                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n232\t                )\n233\t            if max_count is not None and actual > max_count:\n234\t                raise TemplateViolation(\n235\t                    f\"Template allows at most {max_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n236\t                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n237\t                )\n238\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7d98639c-26bc-45d3-9705-9d67800b0669","uuid":"b5d4f639-e0f3-49d0-bcb2-4b29749ad889","timestamp":"2026-04-09T04:26:51.285Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-227.2-prd-implementation-template/src/darkfactory/templates.py","content":"\"\"\"Prompt file loading, variable substitution, and WorkflowTemplate abstraction.\n\nWhen the runner executes an :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.AgentTask`,\nit needs to build the prompt the Claude Code subprocess will receive.\nThat involves three steps:\n\n1. **Load** each file listed in ``AgentTask.prompts``, resolved\n   relative to the workflow's directory.\n2. **Concatenate** them with blank-line separators, preserving order.\n3. **Substitute** ``{{PLACEHOLDER}}``-style tokens with values from\n   the current :class:`~darkfactory.workflow.ExecutionContext`.\n\nThe placeholder syntax (``{{UPPERCASE_NAME}}``) is deliberately distinct\nfrom Python's ``str.format`` ``{lowercase}`` style used by\n``ExecutionContext.format_string`` — the two templating systems serve\ndifferent purposes:\n\n- :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` is **strict**: unknown\n  placeholders raise ``KeyError``. Used for commit messages and shell\n  commands where typos must be caught early.\n- :func:`substitute_placeholders` is **permissive**: unknown\n  placeholders are left as-is. This lets agent prompts evolve\n  incrementally — you can reference ``{{NEW_FIELD}}`` in a prompt\n  before the context learns how to populate it, and the prompt still\n  renders without exploding.\n\nThe split also prevents accidental collisions between Python format\nstrings in Bash commands and agent-prompt placeholders.\n\n:class:`WorkflowTemplate` is the foundational primitive for PRD-227\nworkflow templates. A template defines required opening tasks, a\nconstrained middle slot, and required closing tasks. ``.compose()``\nconcatenates ``[*open, *middle, *close]`` into a :class:`Workflow`,\nvalidating the middle against ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``\nconstraints.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport re\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Mapping\n\nfrom .workflow import BuiltIn, Workflow\n\nif TYPE_CHECKING:\n    from .workflow import ExecutionContext\n\n\nPLACEHOLDER_RE = re.compile(r\"\\{\\{(\\w+)\\}\\}\")\n\"\"\"Matches ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in prompt templates.\n\nThe captured group is the placeholder name (alphanumeric + underscore).\nNon-matching sequences pass through unchanged, so literal ``{{ }}`` in\ndocumentation or code blocks inside prompts survive the substitution.\n\"\"\"\n\n\ndef load_prompt_files(workflow_dir: Path, paths: list[str]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Read and concatenate prompt files from a workflow directory.\n\n    Each path in ``paths`` is resolved relative to ``workflow_dir`` and\n    read as UTF-8. Results are joined with ``\"\\\\n\\\\n\"`` separators so the\n    agent sees them as distinct sections rather than one run-on prompt.\n\n    Raises ``FileNotFoundError`` with the workflow directory in the\n    message if any path doesn't resolve — typos in ``AgentTask.prompts``\n    should fail loudly at runtime, not silently produce empty prompts.\n    \"\"\"\n    parts: list[str] = []\n    for path in paths:\n        full = workflow_dir / path\n        if not full.exists():\n            raise FileNotFoundError(\n                f\"prompt file not found in workflow {workflow_dir.name!r}: {path} \"\n                f\"(looked in {full})\"\n            )\n        parts.append(full.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\"))\n    return \"\\n\\n\".join(parts)\n\n\ndef substitute_placeholders(template: str, context: Mapping[str, object]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Replace ``{{NAME}}`` tokens in ``template`` using ``context``.\n\n    Unknown placeholders (names not in ``context``) are left unchanged.\n    This is intentional — it lets prompt authors reference future\n    placeholders without breaking the current rendering, and it means a\n    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` reference in verify.md stays literal during\n    the initial rendering pass (when no check has failed yet) and gets\n    substituted only on retry.\n\n    Values are coerced to ``str`` via ``str()``, so integers, paths,\n    and dataclass reprs all work without caller ceremony.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def replace(match: re.Match[str]) -> str:\n        key = match.group(1)\n        if key in context:\n            return str(context[key])\n        return match.group(0)  # leave unchanged\n\n    return PLACEHOLDER_RE.sub(replace, template)\n\n\ndef compose_prompt(\n    workflow: Workflow,\n    prompts: list[str],\n    execution_context: ExecutionContext,\n    extras: Mapping[str, object] | None = None,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"End-to-end: load prompt files and substitute context placeholders.\n\n    The standard placeholder set populated from the ExecutionContext:\n\n    - ``{{PRD_ID}}`` — the PRD's id\n    - ``{{PRD_TITLE}}`` — the PRD's title\n    - ``{{PRD_PATH}}`` — absolute path to the PRD file\n    - ``{{PRD_SLUG}}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n    - ``{{BRANCH_NAME}}`` — the current branch name\n    - ``{{BASE_REF}}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n    - ``{{WORKTREE_PATH}}`` — the worktree path (or empty string if unset)\n\n    ``extras`` is merged into the context after the standard keys, so\n    callers can inject ad-hoc values (e.g. ``CHECK_OUTPUT`` for retry\n    prompts) without modifying the ExecutionContext.\n\n    Raises ``ValueError`` if the workflow has no ``workflow_dir`` set\n    (shouldn't happen in practice — the loader sets it — but makes the\n    failure explicit if someone constructs a Workflow by hand).\n    \"\"\"\n    if workflow.workflow_dir is None:\n        raise ValueError(\n            f\"workflow {workflow.name!r} has no workflow_dir; \"\n            \"the loader normally sets this at import time\"\n        )\n\n    raw = load_prompt_files(workflow.workflow_dir, prompts)\n\n    prd = execution_context.prd\n    context: dict[str, object] = {\n        \"PRD_ID\": prd.id,\n        \"PRD_TITLE\": prd.title,\n        \"PRD_PATH\": str(prd.path),\n        \"PRD_SLUG\": prd.slug,\n        \"BRANCH_NAME\": execution_context.branch_name,\n        \"BASE_REF\": execution_context.base_ref,\n        \"WORKTREE_PATH\": (\n            str(execution_context.worktree_path)\n            if execution_context.worktree_path\n            else \"\"\n        ),\n    }\n    if extras:\n        context.update(extras)\n\n    return substitute_placeholders(raw, context)\n\n\n# ---------- WorkflowTemplate ----------\n\n\nclass TemplateViolation(Exception):\n    \"\"\"Raised when a composed middle violates the template's constraints.\"\"\"\n\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass WorkflowTemplate:\n    \"\"\"A reusable recipe that stamps out :class:`Workflow` instances.\n\n    A template defines:\n\n    - Required **opening** tasks that always run first (``open``).\n    - A constrained **middle** slot for caller-supplied tasks.\n    - Required **closing** tasks that always run last (``close``).\n\n    :meth:`compose` validates the caller's middle tasks against\n    ``middle_kinds`` and ``middle_required``, then returns a\n    :class:`Workflow` whose task list is ``[*open, *middle, *close]``\n    with ``template_name`` set to this template's ``name``.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    open: list[BuiltIn]\n    close: list[BuiltIn]\n    middle_kinds: list[type] = field(default_factory=list)\n    middle_required: dict[type, tuple[int, int | None]] = field(default_factory=dict)\n\n    def compose(\n        self,\n        name: str,\n        description: str,\n        applies_to: Callable[..., bool],\n        priority: int,\n        middle: list[Any],\n    ) -> Workflow:\n        \"\"\"Validate ``middle`` and return a complete :class:`Workflow`.\n\n        Parameters match :class:`Workflow` constructor arguments for the\n        caller-supplied fields. ``tasks`` and ``template_name`` are set\n        by this method.\n\n        Raises :class:`TemplateViolation` if any task in ``middle`` is\n        not an instance of one of ``middle_kinds``, or if the count of\n        any required kind falls outside the ``middle_required`` bounds.\n        \"\"\"\n        self._validate_middle(middle)\n        return Workflow(\n            name=name,\n            description=description,\n            applies_to=applies_to,\n            priority=priority,\n            tasks=[*self.open, *middle, *self.close],\n            template_name=self.name,\n        )\n\n    def _validate_middle(self, middle: list[Any]) -> None:\n        if self.middle_kinds:\n            for task in middle:\n                if not isinstance(task, tuple(self.middle_kinds)):\n                    raise TemplateViolation(\n                        f\"Task {task!r} is not an allowed middle kind \"\n                        f\"(allowed: {[k.__name__ for k in self.middle_kinds]})\"\n                    )\n        for kind, (min_count, max_count) in self.middle_required.items():\n            actual = sum(1 for t in middle if isinstance(t, kind))\n            if actual < min_count:\n                raise TemplateViolation(\n                    f\"Template requires at least {min_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n                )\n            if max_count is not None and actual > max_count:\n                raise TemplateViolation(\n                    f\"Template allows at most {max_count} {kind.__name__} \"\n                    f\"in the middle, got {actual}\"\n                )\n","numLines":238,"startLine":1,"totalLines":238}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MFaKRaPZMhceVMKQLZSJrq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BXvw1dNUCoqqXfSAGUdhDH","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-227.2-prd-implementation-template/src/darkfactory/workflow.py"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":346,"cache_read_input_tokens":20369,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":346},"output_tokens":63,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7d98639c-26bc-45d3-9705-9d67800b0669","uuid":"c602ab2f-d59b-46ba-8790-96b6a5009cc7"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BXvw1dNUCoqqXfSAGUdhDH","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"Declarative workflow definitions for the PRD harness.\n2\t\n3\tA ``Workflow`` is a named, ordered list of ``Task`` s that implement one\n4\tkind of PRD. Three task types compose a workflow:\n5\t\n6\t- :class:`BuiltIn` — reference a deterministic primitive by name. The\n7\t  set is fixed by the harness package (``builtins.py``): ``ensure_worktree``,\n8\t  ``set_status``, ``commit``, ``push_branch``, ``create_pr``, etc.\n9\t- :class:`AgentTask` — invoke Claude Code with composed prompts, a tool\n10\t  allowlist, and a model selection. This is the only task type where\n11\t  actual code gets written.\n12\t- :class:`ShellTask` — run a deterministic shell command inside the\n13\t  worktree. Used for verification (``just test``, ``pnpm storybook:build``)\n14\t  with an ``on_failure`` policy.\n15\t\n16\tWorkflows live in ``tools/prd-harness/workflows/<name>/workflow.py`` modules\n17\tthat export a top-level ``workflow`` attribute. The loader discovers them\n18\tand the runner dispatches each task in order against an\n19\t:class:`ExecutionContext` that threads mutable state (worktree path, branch\n20\tname, agent output, PR URL, etc.) between tasks.\n21\t\n22\tThis module intentionally contains no I/O, no subprocess calls, and no\n23\tdependency on ``prd.py`` at import time. It's pure data — the shapes that\n24\tworkflow authors and the runner both plug into.\n25\t\"\"\"\n26\t\n27\tfrom __future__ import annotations\n28\t\n29\timport logging\n30\tfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n31\tfrom pathlib import Path\n32\tfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Literal\n33\t\n34\tif TYPE_CHECKING:\n35\t    from filelock import FileLock\n36\t\n37\t    from .invoke import InvokeResult\n38\t    from .prd import PRD\n39\t\n40\t\n41\t# ---------- type aliases ----------\n42\t\n43\t\n44\tOnFailure = Literal[\"fail\", \"retry_agent\", \"ignore\"]\n45\t\"\"\"Policy for a :class:`ShellTask` when the command exits non-zero.\n46\t\n47\t- ``\"fail\"``: abort the workflow with an error (default).\n48\t- ``\"retry_agent\"``: re-invoke the preceding :class:`AgentTask` once with\n49\t  the verify prompts and the failed check output, then retry the shell\n50\t  task once. If it still fails, abort.\n51\t- ``\"ignore\"``: log the failure and continue with the next task. Useful\n52\t  for advisory checks that shouldn't block progress.\n53\t\"\"\"\n54\t\n55\t\n56\tStatus = Literal[\n57\t    \"draft\", \"ready\", \"in-progress\", \"review\", \"done\", \"blocked\", \"cancelled\"\n58\t]\n59\t\"\"\"All PRD lifecycle statuses. Mirrors the enum in ``docs/prd/_schema.yaml``.\"\"\"\n60\t\n61\t\n62\tAppliesToPredicate = Callable[[\"PRD\", dict[str, \"PRD\"]], bool]\n63\t\"\"\"Two-argument predicate deciding whether a workflow applies to a PRD.\n64\t\n65\tTakes the target PRD plus the full PRD set so predicates that need\n66\tsibling or ancestor context (e.g. ``planning`` checking\n67\t``is_fully_decomposed``) can reach for it. Simple predicates like\n68\t``lambda prd, prds: \"ui\" in prd.tags`` ignore the second argument.\n69\t\"\"\"\n70\t\n71\t\n72\t# ---------- Task hierarchy ----------\n73\t\n74\t\n75\tclass Task:\n76\t    \"\"\"Marker base class for all task types.\n77\t\n78\t    Deliberately not a ``@dataclass`` — subclasses define their own fields\n79\t    and don't share any, so dataclass inheritance would add complexity with\n80\t    no benefit. The class exists purely for ``isinstance()`` dispatch in\n81\t    the runner's task loop.\n82\t    \"\"\"\n83\t\n84\t\n85\t@dataclass\n86\tclass BuiltIn(Task):\n87\t    \"\"\"Reference a deterministic primitive from the ``BUILTINS`` registry.\n88\t\n89\t    The runner looks up ``name`` in ``darkfactory.builtins.BUILTINS`` and\n90\t    calls the registered function with ``(ctx, **kwargs)``. String values\n91\t    in ``kwargs`` are formatted via :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string`\n92\t    before the call, so workflow authors can use ``{prd_id}``-style\n93\t    placeholders.\n94\t\n95\t    Example::\n96\t\n97\t        BuiltIn(\"commit\", kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"})\n98\t\n99\t    The runner resolves ``{prd_id}`` at execution time; the workflow\n100\t    definition stays free of runtime state.\n101\t    \"\"\"\n102\t\n103\t    name: str\n104\t    kwargs: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n105\t\n106\t\n107\t@dataclass\n108\tclass AgentTask(Task):\n109\t    \"\"\"Invoke Claude Code with composed prompts and a restricted tool allowlist.\n110\t\n111\t    The runner (see ``runner.py``) performs these steps:\n112\t\n113\t    1. Read each path in :attr:`prompts` relative to the workflow's\n114\t       directory (set by the loader) and concatenate the file contents.\n115\t    2. Substitute ``{{PRD_ID}}``/``{{PRD_TITLE}}``/``{{PRD_PATH}}``/etc.\n116\t       placeholders against the :class:`ExecutionContext` via\n117\t       ``templates.substitute_placeholders``.\n118\t    3. Pick a model: :attr:`model` if explicitly set, else map from\n119\t       ``ctx.prd.capability`` when :attr:`model_from_capability` is\n120\t       true, else fall back to sonnet.\n121\t    4. Pipe the composed prompt to ``claude --print`` via subprocess with\n122\t       ``--allowed-tools`` set to :attr:`tools`.\n123\t    5. Parse stdout for :attr:`sentinel_success` or :attr:`sentinel_failure`\n124\t       to decide whether the task succeeded. The agent is contracted to\n125\t       emit one of these as its final line.\n126\t\n127\t    When a subsequent :class:`ShellTask` fails with\n128\t    ``on_failure=\"retry_agent\"``, the runner re-invokes this AgentTask\n129\t    with :attr:`verify_prompts` prepended to the prompt list and\n130\t    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` bound to the failed stdout/stderr — at most\n131\t    :attr:`retries` times.\n132\t    \"\"\"\n133\t\n134\t    name: str = \"implement\"\n135\t    prompts: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n136\t    tools: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n137\t    model: str | None = None\n138\t    model_from_capability: bool = True\n139\t    retries: int = 1\n140\t    verify_prompts: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n141\t    sentinel_success: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_OK\"\n142\t    sentinel_failure: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED\"\n143\t\n144\t\n145\t@dataclass\n146\tclass ShellTask(Task):\n147\t    \"\"\"Run a deterministic shell command inside the worktree.\n148\t\n149\t    ``cmd`` is formatted via :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` before\n150\t    execution (so ``{worktree}`` etc. placeholders are expanded) and runs\n151\t    with ``cwd=ctx.cwd`` (the worktree path after ``ensure_worktree``).\n152\t    ``env`` is merged into the subprocess environment.\n153\t\n154\t    :attr:`on_failure` controls the recovery path on non-zero exit. See\n155\t    the :data:`OnFailure` type alias for policy semantics.\n156\t    \"\"\"\n157\t\n158\t    name: str\n159\t    cmd: str\n160\t    on_failure: OnFailure = \"fail\"\n161\t    env: dict[str, str] = field(default_factory=dict)\n162\t\n163\t\n164\t# ---------- Workflow ----------\n165\t\n166\t\n167\tdef _default_applies_to(prd: \"PRD\", prds: dict[str, \"PRD\"]) -> bool:\n168\t    \"\"\"Default ``applies_to`` predicate — matches nothing.\n169\t\n170\t    Concrete workflows override this in their ``workflow.py`` module.\n171\t    Kept as a module-level function rather than a lambda so mypy and\n172\t    pickling (if ever needed) both behave.\n173\t    \"\"\"\n174\t    return False\n175\t\n176\t\n177\t@dataclass\n178\tclass Workflow:\n179\t    \"\"\"A named recipe for implementing one kind of PRD.\n180\t\n181\t    Authored in ``tools/prd-harness/workflows/<name>/workflow.py`` as a\n182\t    module-level ``workflow = Workflow(...)`` attribute. The loader\n183\t    discovers it, imports the module, and sets :attr:`workflow_dir` to\n184\t    the subdirectory path so AgentTask prompt paths resolve correctly.\n185\t\n186\t    :attr:`priority` orders workflows during assignment: higher numbers\n187\t    win when multiple predicates match. ``default`` has priority 0 and\n188\t    acts as a catchall. Ties are broken alphabetically by name.\n189\t    \"\"\"\n190\t\n191\t    name: str\n192\t    description: str = \"\"\n193\t    applies_to: AppliesToPredicate = field(default=_default_applies_to)\n194\t    priority: int = 0\n195\t    tasks: list[Task] = field(default_factory=list)\n196\t    workflow_dir: Path | None = None\n197\t    template_name: str | None = None\n198\t\n199\t\n200\t# ---------- ExecutionContext ----------\n201\t\n202\t\n203\t@dataclass\n204\tclass ExecutionContext:\n205\t    \"\"\"State threaded through every task during a workflow run.\n206\t\n207\t    Tasks mutate this object in place as the workflow progresses:\n208\t\n209\t    - ``ensure_worktree`` sets :attr:`worktree_path` and :attr:`cwd`\n210\t    - The agent invoke populates :attr:`agent_output` and\n211\t      :attr:`agent_success`\n212\t    - ``create_pr`` sets :attr:`pr_url`\n213\t\n214\t    The runner creates one context at the start of ``run_workflow`` and\n215\t    passes it to each task in order. Tasks read from it (for formatting\n216\t    commit messages, composing prompts, etc.) and write to it (to record\n217\t    side effects for downstream tasks or the CLI to surface).\n218\t\n219\t    :attr:`dry_run` tells builtins, shell tasks, and the agent invoke to\n220\t    log what they WOULD do without actually invoking subprocesses, git,\n221\t    or gh. Drives the ``prd plan`` output.\n222\t    \"\"\"\n223\t\n224\t    prd: \"PRD\"\n225\t    repo_root: Path\n226\t    workflow: Workflow\n227\t    base_ref: str\n228\t    branch_name: str\n229\t    worktree_path: Path | None = None\n230\t    cwd: Path = field(default_factory=Path.cwd)\n231\t    agent_output: str | None = None\n232\t    agent_success: bool = False\n233\t    pr_url: str | None = None\n234\t    run_summary: str | None = None\n235\t    last_invoke_result: \"InvokeResult | None\" = None\n236\t    model: str | None = None\n237\t    invoke_count: int = 0\n238\t    dry_run: bool = True\n239\t    logger: logging.Logger = field(\n240\t        default_factory=lambda: logging.getLogger(\"darkfactory\")\n241\t    )\n242\t    # Advisory process-level lock held by ensure_worktree for the\n243\t    # lifetime of this run. Managed by builtins + runner; tests should\n244\t    # not touch it directly.\n245\t    _worktree_lock: \"FileLock | None\" = field(default=None, repr=False)\n246\t\n247\t    def format_string(self, template: str) -> str:\n248\t        \"\"\"Expand ``{placeholder}`` tokens against context state.\n249\t\n250\t        Supported placeholders:\n251\t\n252\t        - ``{prd_id}`` — the PRD's id (e.g. ``PRD-070``)\n253\t        - ``{prd_title}`` — the PRD's title\n254\t        - ``{prd_slug}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n255\t        - ``{branch}`` — the current branch name\n256\t        - ``{base_ref}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n257\t        - ``{worktree}`` — the worktree path as a string, or ``\"\"`` if\n258\t          the worktree hasn't been created yet\n259\t\n260\t        Unknown placeholders raise ``KeyError`` (intentionally strict —\n261\t        workflow authors should catch typos early). Contrast with the\n262\t        agent prompt templater in ``templates.py``, which leaves unknown\n263\t        placeholders unchanged to allow incremental template evolution.\n264\t        \"\"\"\n265\t        return template.format(\n266\t            prd_id=self.prd.id,\n267\t            prd_title=self.prd.title,\n268\t            prd_slug=self.prd.slug,\n269\t            branch=self.branch_name,\n270\t            base_ref=self.base_ref,\n271\t            worktree=str(self.worktree_path) if self.worktree_path else \"\",\n272\t        )\n273\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7d98639c-26bc-45d3-9705-9d67800b0669","uuid":"36fe0758-8558-4182-adcc-4523996d5914","timestamp":"2026-04-09T04:26:51.928Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-227.2-prd-implementation-template/src/darkfactory/workflow.py","content":"\"\"\"Declarative workflow definitions for the PRD harness.\n\nA ``Workflow`` is a named, ordered list of ``Task`` s that implement one\nkind of PRD. Three task types compose a workflow:\n\n- :class:`BuiltIn` — reference a deterministic primitive by name. The\n  set is fixed by the harness package (``builtins.py``): ``ensure_worktree``,\n  ``set_status``, ``commit``, ``push_branch``, ``create_pr``, etc.\n- :class:`AgentTask` — invoke Claude Code with composed prompts, a tool\n  allowlist, and a model selection. This is the only task type where\n  actual code gets written.\n- :class:`ShellTask` — run a deterministic shell command inside the\n  worktree. Used for verification (``just test``, ``pnpm storybook:build``)\n  with an ``on_failure`` policy.\n\nWorkflows live in ``tools/prd-harness/workflows/<name>/workflow.py`` modules\nthat export a top-level ``workflow`` attribute. The loader discovers them\nand the runner dispatches each task in order against an\n:class:`ExecutionContext` that threads mutable state (worktree path, branch\nname, agent output, PR URL, etc.) between tasks.\n\nThis module intentionally contains no I/O, no subprocess calls, and no\ndependency on ``prd.py`` at import time. It's pure data — the shapes that\nworkflow authors and the runner both plug into.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Literal\n\nif TYPE_CHECKING:\n    from filelock import FileLock\n\n    from .invoke import InvokeResult\n    from .prd import PRD\n\n\n# ---------- type aliases ----------\n\n\nOnFailure = Literal[\"fail\", \"retry_agent\", \"ignore\"]\n\"\"\"Policy for a :class:`ShellTask` when the command exits non-zero.\n\n- ``\"fail\"``: abort the workflow with an error (default).\n- ``\"retry_agent\"``: re-invoke the preceding :class:`AgentTask` once with\n  the verify prompts and the failed check output, then retry the shell\n  task once. If it still fails, abort.\n- ``\"ignore\"``: log the failure and continue with the next task. Useful\n  for advisory checks that shouldn't block progress.\n\"\"\"\n\n\nStatus = Literal[\n    \"draft\", \"ready\", \"in-progress\", \"review\", \"done\", \"blocked\", \"cancelled\"\n]\n\"\"\"All PRD lifecycle statuses. Mirrors the enum in ``docs/prd/_schema.yaml``.\"\"\"\n\n\nAppliesToPredicate = Callable[[\"PRD\", dict[str, \"PRD\"]], bool]\n\"\"\"Two-argument predicate deciding whether a workflow applies to a PRD.\n\nTakes the target PRD plus the full PRD set so predicates that need\nsibling or ancestor context (e.g. ``planning`` checking\n``is_fully_decomposed``) can reach for it. Simple predicates like\n``lambda prd, prds: \"ui\" in prd.tags`` ignore the second argument.\n\"\"\"\n\n\n# ---------- Task hierarchy ----------\n\n\nclass Task:\n    \"\"\"Marker base class for all task types.\n\n    Deliberately not a ``@dataclass`` — subclasses define their own fields\n    and don't share any, so dataclass inheritance would add complexity with\n    no benefit. The class exists purely for ``isinstance()`` dispatch in\n    the runner's task loop.\n    \"\"\"\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass BuiltIn(Task):\n    \"\"\"Reference a deterministic primitive from the ``BUILTINS`` registry.\n\n    The runner looks up ``name`` in ``darkfactory.builtins.BUILTINS`` and\n    calls the registered function with ``(ctx, **kwargs)``. String values\n    in ``kwargs`` are formatted via :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string`\n    before the call, so workflow authors can use ``{prd_id}``-style\n    placeholders.\n\n    Example::\n\n        BuiltIn(\"commit\", kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"})\n\n    The runner resolves ``{prd_id}`` at execution time; the workflow\n    definition stays free of runtime state.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str\n    kwargs: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass AgentTask(Task):\n    \"\"\"Invoke Claude Code with composed prompts and a restricted tool allowlist.\n\n    The runner (see ``runner.py``) performs these steps:\n\n    1. Read each path in :attr:`prompts` relative to the workflow's\n       directory (set by the loader) and concatenate the file contents.\n    2. Substitute ``{{PRD_ID}}``/``{{PRD_TITLE}}``/``{{PRD_PATH}}``/etc.\n       placeholders against the :class:`ExecutionContext` via\n       ``templates.substitute_placeholders``.\n    3. Pick a model: :attr:`model` if explicitly set, else map from\n       ``ctx.prd.capability`` when :attr:`model_from_capability` is\n       true, else fall back to sonnet.\n    4. Pipe the composed prompt to ``claude --print`` via subprocess with\n       ``--allowed-tools`` set to :attr:`tools`.\n    5. Parse stdout for :attr:`sentinel_success` or :attr:`sentinel_failure`\n       to decide whether the task succeeded. The agent is contracted to\n       emit one of these as its final line.\n\n    When a subsequent :class:`ShellTask` fails with\n    ``on_failure=\"retry_agent\"``, the runner re-invokes this AgentTask\n    with :attr:`verify_prompts` prepended to the prompt list and\n    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` bound to the failed stdout/stderr — at most\n    :attr:`retries` times.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str = \"implement\"\n    prompts: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n    tools: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n    model: str | None = None\n    model_from_capability: bool = True\n    retries: int = 1\n    verify_prompts: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n    sentinel_success: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_OK\"\n    sentinel_failure: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED\"\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass ShellTask(Task):\n    \"\"\"Run a deterministic shell command inside the worktree.\n\n    ``cmd`` is formatted via :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` before\n    execution (so ``{worktree}`` etc. placeholders are expanded) and runs\n    with ``cwd=ctx.cwd`` (the worktree path after ``ensure_worktree``).\n    ``env`` is merged into the subprocess environment.\n\n    :attr:`on_failure` controls the recovery path on non-zero exit. See\n    the :data:`OnFailure` type alias for policy semantics.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str\n    cmd: str\n    on_failure: OnFailure = \"fail\"\n    env: dict[str, str] = field(default_factory=dict)\n\n\n# ---------- Workflow ----------\n\n\ndef _default_applies_to(prd: \"PRD\", prds: dict[str, \"PRD\"]) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Default ``applies_to`` predicate — matches nothing.\n\n    Concrete workflows override this in their ``workflow.py`` module.\n    Kept as a module-level function rather than a lambda so mypy and\n    pickling (if ever needed) both behave.\n    \"\"\"\n    return False\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass Workflow:\n    \"\"\"A named recipe for implementing one kind of PRD.\n\n    Authored in ``tools/prd-harness/workflows/<name>/workflow.py`` as a\n    module-level ``workflow = Workflow(...)`` attribute. The loader\n    discovers it, imports the module, and sets :attr:`workflow_dir` to\n    the subdirectory path so AgentTask prompt paths resolve correctly.\n\n    :attr:`priority` orders workflows during assignment: higher numbers\n    win when multiple predicates match. ``default`` has priority 0 and\n    acts as a catchall. Ties are broken alphabetically by name.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str\n    description: str = \"\"\n    applies_to: AppliesToPredicate = field(default=_default_applies_to)\n    priority: int = 0\n    tasks: list[Task] = field(default_factory=list)\n    workflow_dir: Path | None = None\n    template_name: str | None = None\n\n\n# ---------- ExecutionContext ----------\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass ExecutionContext:\n    \"\"\"State threaded through every task during a workflow run.\n\n    Tasks mutate this object in place as the workflow progresses:\n\n    - ``ensure_worktree`` sets :attr:`worktree_path` and :attr:`cwd`\n    - The agent invoke populates :attr:`agent_output` and\n      :attr:`agent_success`\n    - ``create_pr`` sets :attr:`pr_url`\n\n    The runner creates one context at the start of ``run_workflow`` and\n    passes it to each task in order. Tasks read from it (for formatting\n    commit messages, composing prompts, etc.) and write to it (to record\n    side effects for downstream tasks or the CLI to surface).\n\n    :attr:`dry_run` tells builtins, shell tasks, and the agent invoke to\n    log what they WOULD do without actually invoking subprocesses, git,\n    or gh. Drives the ``prd plan`` output.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    prd: \"PRD\"\n    repo_root: Path\n    workflow: Workflow\n    base_ref: str\n    branch_name: str\n    worktree_path: Path | None = None\n    cwd: Path = field(default_factory=Path.cwd)\n    agent_output: str | None = None\n    agent_success: bool = False\n    pr_url: str | None = None\n    run_summary: str | None = None\n    last_invoke_result: \"InvokeResult | None\" = None\n    model: str | None = None\n    invoke_count: int = 0\n    dry_run: bool = True\n    logger: logging.Logger = field(\n        default_factory=lambda: logging.getLogger(\"darkfactory\")\n    )\n    # Advisory process-level lock held by ensure_worktree for the\n    # lifetime of this run. Managed by builtins + runner; tests should\n    # not touch it directly.\n    _worktree_lock: \"FileLock | None\" = field(default=None, repr=False)\n\n    def format_string(self, template: str) -> str:\n        \"\"\"Expand ``{placeholder}`` tokens against context state.\n\n        Supported placeholders:\n\n        - ``{prd_id}`` — the PRD's id (e.g. ``PRD-070``)\n        - ``{prd_title}`` — the PRD's title\n        - ``{prd_slug}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n        - ``{branch}`` — the current branch name\n        - ``{base_ref}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n        - ``{worktree}`` — the worktree path as a string, or ``\"\"`` if\n          the worktree hasn't been created yet\n\n        Unknown placeholders raise ``KeyError`` (intentionally strict —\n        workflow authors should catch typos early). Contrast with the\n        agent prompt templater in ``templates.py``, which leaves unknown\n        placeholders unchanged to allow incremental template evolution.\n        \"\"\"\n        return template.format(\n            prd_id=self.prd.id,\n            prd_title=self.prd.title,\n            prd_slug=self.prd.slug,\n            branch=self.branch_name,\n            base_ref=self.base_ref,\n            worktree=str(self.worktree_path) if self.worktree_path else \"\",\n        )\n","numLines":273,"startLine":1,"totalLines":273}}}
